      "SummaryText": "Risk Management Plan Executive Summary for Pennakem, LLC Memphis, Tennessee Facility\n\n1.\tAccidental Release Prevention and Emergency Response Policies\nWe at Pennakem LLC Memphis Plant are strongly committed to employee, public and environmental safety.  This commitment is evidenced by a comprehensive accidental release prevention program that covers areas such as design, installation, operating procedures, maintenance, and employee training associated with the processes at our facility.  It is our policy to implement appropriate controls to prevent possible releases of regulated substances.  Unforeseeably, if such a release does occur, the Memphis site utilizes the highly trained local Memphis Fire and contractors to control and mitigate the effects of the release. \n\n2.\tThe Stationary Source and the Regulated Substances Handled\nOur facility's primary activities encompass Organic chemical synthesis.  We have 4 RMP toxic and flammable substances regulated at our facility.  The substance Furan is involved in several uses throughout plant including as a raw material and a commercial chemical product.  There is also Cyclohexylamine, Aqueous Ammonia, and Dimethylamine 40% which are used as raw materials in our specialties product manufacturing area to make other commercial chemical products.  Unlike Furan that is piped and used throughout the plant, these chemicals are stored in isolated locations in totes/drums and a small tank (DMA). \n\n3.\tThe Worst-Case Release Scenario and the Alternative Release Scenarios, including administrative controls and mitigation measures to limit the distances for each reported scenario. In order to perform the required off-site consequence analysis, the Pennakem Memphis facility used EPA's RMP COMP software.  While Pennakem Memphis has a program to respond to a release of furan, this worst-case scenario does not allow any active mitigation to be considered and further requires the release to occur under conditions that are not indicative of"
