      "SummaryText": "any conditions which have been encountered. The following paragraphs provide details of both the worst case release scenario and the alternative release scenario.\n\nThe worst-case release scenario submitted for Program 3 toxic substances involves a release of furan over a short period of time.  The furan liquid is assumed to be immediately released from a total tank failure, in which evaporation takes place. Cyclohexylamine and Aqueous Ammonia were the other Program 3 toxic substance submitted as alternative scenarios. These substances are stored in totes and drums and most likely would have a event that includes puncturing or rupturing of the drum/totes.  One alternative release scenario is included for furan as part of the Program 3 processes. The alternative release scenario allows use of active and passive mitigation.\n\nThe worst-case release scenario submitted for Program 3 flammable substances also involves releasing dimethylamine (DMA) over a short period of time.  However, DMA is aquesous solution and is stored and used from a tank.  An alternative release scenario for this flammable substance was also evaluated.\n\n4.  The General Accidental Release Prevention Program and the Chemical-Specific Prevention Steps\nOur facility has taken all the necessary steps to comply with the accidental release prevention requirements set out under 40 CFR part 68 of the EPA.  This facility was designed and constructed in accordance with State Building codes.  A number of processes at our facility are subject to the OSHA PSM standard under 29 CFR 1910.119 including the one containing furan.  Our facility is also subject to EPCRA Section 302 notification requirements.    The following sections briefly describe the elements of the release prevention program.\n\nProcess Safety Information\nPennakem, LLC Memphis Plant maintains a detailed record of safety information that describes the chemical hazards, operating parameters and equipment designs associated with all processes.\n\nProcess H"
